<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STRENGTH of the stock index futures sector was tested yesterday when the
outcome of the auction in the UK gilt-edged market briefly cast a cloud over
equities, writes Terry Byland.
Traders admitted that there was some selling of both equities and the
December contract on the Footsie, although both sectors rallied before the
close of business.
Some good-sized buying was reported in the first half-hour of trading but
confidence was soon undermined when bonds turned down. The December contract
bounced against its fair value several times before rallying to close at a
premium of 32 against the cash market. This showed a premium of around 8
points above fair value, the estimated premium which allows for dividend and
financing flows. Trading volume was down to 9,026 contracts, which traders
considered a satisfactory level for the penultimate trading session of the
third quarter of the year.
Activity in traded options was around one-third lower at 23,364 contracts.
The FT-SE 100 option, at 9,354 lots, recorded a sharp fall from Tuesday's
total of just above 18,000. The Euro FT-SE option was fairly busy at 3,436
contracts, while BP headed the list of individual stock options, turning
over 2,110 deals as the market continued to track the Opec meeting. Also
attracting interest was Tesco (1,103 contracts).
</TEXT>
