<DATE>930930
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / World Stock Markets: Venezuela strengthens ahead of
elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Venezuela showed the best performance in dollar terms last week among the
world's emerging markets as investors reacted positively to comments by Mr
Rafael Caldera, the independent candidate in the forthcoming presidential
elections.
Nevertheless, specialists in the market remain nervous about the medium term
direction of equities, and forecast unsettled trading ahead of polling day,
scheduled for the beginning of December.
Mr Federico Laffan of Latin American Securities says that a number of
factors encouraged trading in Venezuela last week. These included comments
by Mr Caldera that, in general, economic and financial reform policies
initiated by the current administration would be continued; an apparent lull
in the recent spate of terrorist bombings; and stability in the level of
int-erest rates, currently at some 50 per cent.
Access to foreign investment in Venezuela is concentrated in ADRs traded in
New York, says Mr Laffan. There are around eight ADRs, a high number for the
region when compared with Colombia's one and Chile's four, and this broad
access has also contributed to the market's rise.
Turkey featured once again last week in the table compiled by the IFC, the
private sector arm of the World Bank. Global Securities in Istanbul comments
that bullish sentiment over nine-month earnings expectations, and enthusiasm
for shares in companies on the government's privatisation list, have
continued to push the market forward.
