<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Money Markets: Liquidity tight
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
CONDITIONS IN the London money market were difficult yesterday, with the
Bank of England slow to remove a Pounds 1.15bn shortage.
The overnight lending rate was stuck between 6 3/4 and 7 per cent in the
morning, before falling to just above 6 per cent in the early afternoon
after the Bank purchased Pounds 670m of bills. Late assistance of Pounds
455m cleared the shortage.
The short sterling futures contract dropped back, partly because the pound
was weakening on the foreign exchanges but also because of lingering
expectations for a rate cut over the next two weeks.
Dealers in the money markets are less convinced of an early rate reduction
than their counterparts in the foreign exchange and equity markets, however.
'We are moving back towards the feeling that we had about three weeks ago
that interest rates are likely to come down at the time of the Budget on
November 30,' said one dealer. 'We do not believe that we are about to see a
rate cut for political reasons, either this week during the Labour party
conference, or next week when the Conservatives meet.'
The December contract dropped as low as 94.34 before closing at around
94.35, down 4 basis points on the day.
The three-month interbank rate was quoted yesterday at 6-5 7/8 per cent,
reflecting scepticism about an early cut in rates.
Dealers are expecting a big shortage today with the close of the month, the
end of the quarter and - for some institutions - the end of the half-year
coinciding. In addition, yesterday's gilts auction needs to be paid for
today, so conditions may well be awkward.
A decision by the Bundesbank to drain the German money market of liquidity
took dealers by surprise. They had expected a more generous allocation of
repo funds in the tender, but in the end the central bank took DM8.5bn from
the system.
All the funds were allocated at 6.7 per cent, with the Bundesbank choosing
not to offer a lower rate.
In spite of the withdrawal of funds, call money edged slightly lower,
indicating that there are ample reserves in the system before the beginning
of next month, when yesterday's repo funds will be credited. Call money was
quoted at 6.80-6.90 per cent yesterday afternoon.
</TEXT>
