<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Accountancy: No room for own goals in financing soccer's
future - Gerry Boon looks at the world of football club accounts and the
implications of putting players on the balance sheet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERRY BOON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENGLISH professional football clubs spent more than Pounds 70m buying
players in the 1991-92 season, but you would never know it from looking at
their balance sheets.
At a time when clubs are increasingly turning to banks and shareholders for
support, should players be treated as a financial asset rather than an
expense to their clubs?
This was one of the questions we set out to answer in the 1993 Touche Ross
survey of football club accounts, published this week. As part of our annual
check on football's financial health, we looked at where the money comes
from to finance football and the accounting implications of putting players
on the balance sheet.
One of the survey's key findings was that in the 1991-92 season, 53 out of
the 84 clubs whose accounts were available reported a pre-tax loss. Add to
this that auditors qualified their reports on the 1992 accounts on 'going
concern' grounds for 27 clubs, and football finances start to look very
sick. But our results give a different picture.
Professional football clubs are increasingly required to pay their way as
businesses. Satellite television deals, new sponsors, tax investigations and
the sale of several clubs is focusing attention on their financial position.
Clubs also face additional burdens unfamiliar to conventional businesses.
For example, the Taylor Report on stadium safety has led to an estimated
Pounds 200m of capital expenditure since its publication in January 1990.
Substantial investment is required to strengthen the quality of players,
because success on the field usually has a direct impact on the club's
finances through greater attendance figures.
Perhaps the greatest challenge is balancing commercial realism against the
demands of the customer, since fans want money spent on players without
having to pay higher ticket prices.
With few exceptions, clubs can no longer rely on wealthy individual backers.
They need to turn to the banks, financial institutions and - like the three
quoted English teams - the Stock Exchange. In order to attract investment,
they will have to portray their financial position in the best commercial
light and demonstrate good financial management.
Our survey highlighted one area - player registrations - in which clubs
could help themselves to promote a more balanced financial picture.
In the 1991-92 season, English first and second division clubs spent Pounds
70m on players, up from Pounds 40 million the previous year. The biggest net
spender was Blackburn Rovers (Pounds 6.84m) followed by Derby County (Pounds
4.44m) and Liverpool (Pounds 3.63m).
But just four clubs put player registrations on the balance sheet as an
intangible asset. And 82 per cent of the 46 clubs in the top two divisions
still account for transfer fees through the profit and loss account in the
year in which the transfers take place.
There are certain advantages to sticking with this traditional way of
accounting for transfer fees. It is uncontroversial, involves no judgment in
carrying forward costs, is simple to understand and disclose, and means all
transfer deals are treated in the same way. It is prudent, consistent with
the way club directors view their transfer fee budget and in line with the
tax treatment of transfer costs.
However, we believe there are two considerable commercial disadvantages to
this policy. First, a substantial 'asset' - the players - is not shown in
the balance sheet. There is a strong business case that this expenditure is
an investment, and not showing it as such conceals the club's true worth.
Second, the profit and loss account bears substantial and 'lumpy' charges
which may significantly distort the underlying results of the business from
year to year. Net transfer income tends to be one of the largest single
items in a club's profit and loss account. For example, Blackburn Rovers'
Pounds 6.84m transfer fees helped result in a pre-tax loss of Pounds 7.92m
in 1991-92.
There are only two ways of expressing the value of transfer fees: either by
an additional disclosure in the accounts or by putting players on the
balance sheet. Derby County, Portsmouth, Sheffield United and Tottenham
Hotspur put players on the balance sheet as an intangible asset. Tottenham
and Derby do so only for players they have bought, which they do at 'cost'.
Sheffield United use the manager's valuation, and Portsmouth uses the
directors' valuation for the whole squad.
Nine clubs disclose the aggregate value of the playing squad in their
accounts, based on either the directors' or manager's valuation. The
exception was Manchester United, which became the first club to have its
squad independently valued. Touche Ross calculated the figure at Pounds 24m,
which analysts quickly converted into 197p per share.
The benefit of an independent valuation is that it lends objective
credibility to the value of the business in the eyes of outsiders:
shareholders, supporters, financiers and investors. The club realised the
importance of communicating its market value to its new audience in the
City.
Club directors, or the team manager, can, of course, produce their own
internal figure. The main advantage is simplicity, although this is perhaps
outweighed by the perceived lack of objectivity. Whatever basis is used,
disclosure of market value for such an important asset is, I believe, good
practice.
It is sometimes argued that disclosing player values is not appropriate
because they are too subjective, or misleading, or simply too difficult to
calculate. Club directors need to tackle certain key issues: whether to use
cost or market value; the period over which to depreciate the capitalised
value; the residual value of a player at the end of his contract; write-offs
in cases of permanent injury; write downs due to a player's loss of form;
and how best to protect tax allowances.
The solutions are fairly straightforward. Market value can be judged from
the prices of recent transfers and other managers' views of what a player is
worth. The depreciation period should not exceed the length of the contract
period, and the standard European Football Association transfer multiplier
(based on a player's age at the end of his contract) can be used to estimate
residual values. A permanent diminution in a player's value because of
injury will require a write-off, although this may be off-set by any
insurance payment received.
The most difficult judgment will be on loss of value because of loss of
form; a reasoned assessment based on what happens elsewhere in the market
will be acceptable. Professional advice should ensure that writing off
transfer fees for tax purposes is not jeopardised by capitalisation.
Our research showed that there is a lot of hidden talent in football absent
from the balance sheet. Based on the disclosed amounts, we estimate that
there is about Pounds 250m in players in the Premier League and Pounds 80m
in the Football League first division - valuable assets that clubs should be
listing alongside their grounds and facilities.
By turning players into an asset rather than showing them as an expense,
clubs can promote themselves as commercial enterprises at a time when
football is coming under greater pressure to perform. If clubs react
positively to the changes, everyone wins: fans, players, clubs, shareholders
and investors.
The author, a partner at Touche Ross in Manchester, is head of the firm's
football industry team. Copies of the survey are available free of charge
from Maxine Johnson on 061-228-3156
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
    P7941 Sports Clubs, Managers, and Promoters.
</IN>
<XX>
