<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / International Company News: Mazda omits dividend as loss
grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MAZDA, the Japanese car-maker 24.5 per cent owned by Ford of the US,
yesterday said its losses this year would be larger than forecast, forcing
it to pass the dividend for the first time.
Pre-tax losses are forecast at Y32bn (Dollars 296m) rather than Y12bn
estimated in May, while sales are expected to fall to Y1,920bn from a
previously forecast Y2,070bn. This would be the company's first loss in 23
years.
The downward revision reflects the severity of the business climate
surrounding Japanese carmakers. Last month, the industry saw exports decline
14.7 per cent, the fifth consecutive monthly fall and the worst performance
in 14 years, according to the Japan Automobile Manufacturers' Association.
Mazda said the loss would arise largely as a result of the yen's sharp
appreciation and a worse-than-expected downturn in the European market.
Mazda does not expect to return to profit next year, since it sees little
hope for a strong recovery in either the Japanese or European markets.
Mr Makoto Miyaji, executive vice-president, said that Mazda hoped to return
to profit and resume dividend payments in fiscal 1995.
The yen's appreciation is expected to shave Y65bn off annual revenues, while
the fall in European sales will make up the bulk of Mazda's expected 18 per
cent decline in sales overseas.
In Europe, Mazda is forecasting an 18 per cent fall in sales to 240,000
units at the retail level, from 292,000 units last year. This compares with
a 16 per cent fall in overall demand in Europe. Unit sales in Japan are
expected to decline 3 per cent to 455,000 units from 470,000 units last
year.
Mazda has introduced restructuring measures, but had not been able to 'catch
up with the changing business environment within a short period', it said.
It is closing a production line in Hiroshima, where it employs about 300,
and shifting its production to other lines.
Restructuring plans will be strengthened and brought forward. Staff levels
will be reduced through natural attrition by 3,000 over the next three
years, rather than 1,500 as planned.
The company is cutting costs and reducing its capital expenditure to Y60bn
from Y80bn last year. It may cut the number of cars in its range to deal
with a slower market, Mr Miyaji said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
