<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / International Company News: Blockbuster agrees Dollars 600m
investment in Viacom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VIACOM, the cable television company, yesterday gained a new ally and
additional financial muscle in its battle to take over Paramount
Communications when Blockbuster Entertainment agreed to invest Dollars 600m
in Viacom.
The deal will give Viacom greater flexibility to increase its agreed offer
for Paramount, which is trailing a rival, hostile offer from QVC Network,
the cable TV home shopping business headed by Mr Barry Diller, a prominent
film industry figure.
Viacom, with interests ranging from cable systems to the MTV pop music TV
channel, declined to comment yesterday on market speculation that it had
been talking to two other companies - regional telephone company
Southwestern Bell and cable systems group Cox Enterprises - in an effort to
secure additional funding.
Blockbuster is a fast-growing Florida-based company which is by far the
largest home video retailer in the US and also runs two large chains of
music stores. It owns the Cityvision video rental company in the UK.
It has also been moving into film production, buying large interests in the
Spelling Entertainment and Republic Entertainment film companies, which are
in the process of merging.
Its investment in Viacom - and thence, it hopes, in Paramount - reinforces
this trend. Paramount owns one of the last large Hollywood studios not part
of a conglomerate.
Blockbuster is buying Dollars 600m of cumulative convertible preferred stock
which is convertible into Viacom's class B, non-voting common stock at a
price of Dollars 70 a share.
If the Viacom-Paramount merger does not go through by next August, either
Blockbuster or Viacom can reduce the investment to Dollars 300m.
Mr Wayne Huizenga, chairman of Blockbuster, who will join the Viacom board,
said the new 'strategic relationship' between the two groups would allow
both to capitalise on their highly complementary businesses. It was, he
added, a strong vote of confidence in the Viacom/Paramount merger.
Wall Street analysts view Blockbuster's move into production partly as
defensive action to protect the company from a potential loss of video
rental business when new technology allows consumers to call up movies on
demand over inter-active home entertainment systems.
Mr Sumner Redstone, chairman of Viacom, said the two companies would pursue
potential ways to benefit from the new relationship after the merger with
Paramount.
Yesterday's deal had a modest impact on the shares of companies involved in
the Paramount battle.
On Wall Street, Viacom's A shares closed Dollars 1 1/2 lower at Dollars 59
1/2 while its B shares dropped Dollars 3/4 to Dollars 55 1/4 valuing its bid
at Dollars 7.7bn.
QVC rose Dollars 1/8 to Dollars 59 5/8, valuing its bid at Dollars 9.8bn.
Paramount closed Dollars 2 higher at Dollars 79 1/2 on growing hopes of an
improved Viacom offer, while Blockbuster fell Dollars 1/4 to Dollars 29.
</TEXT>
