<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / International Company News: Alcatel Alsthom stable at FFr3bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALCATEL Alsthom, the French telecommunications and engineering group,
resisted the impact of recession in some of its principal markets to
announce stable first-half net profits of FFr3.01bn (Dollars 519m).
The results for the first half of the year released yesterday compared with
net profits of FFr3.12bn in the first six months of 1992, but did not
include any exceptional gains. In the first half of last year, Alcatel
Alsthom received a capital gain of FFr440m resulting from the sale of shares
in the group.
The results follow confirmation that the company is to take a 2 per cent
stake in Fiat as part of the Italian group's plan to raise L5,000bn (Dollars
3.2bn) in new capital.
Alcatel Alsthom will represent part of a stable core of shareholders in the
Italian company, which will hold a reciprocal 2 per cent stake in the French
group.
The company said the trends in the first half are expected to continue for
the rest of the year and full-year profits should be equivalent to the
FFr7.05bn achieved in 1992.
Mr Andre Wettstein, executive vice-president in charge of finance, said the
first-half performance had been constrained by the economic downturn in
Germany and Italy. But he added that the group was well placed to benefit
from an upturn.
In Germany, the group's single biggest market for telecommunications and
cables, orders remained strong. Sales, which fell to FFr73.63bn in the first
six months from FFr79.48bn in the first half of 1992, were expected to
decline by between 5 per cent and 7 per cent for the full year.
In Asia, the company said important contracts had been won in all its core
business areas, including a Dollars 1.25bn deal for a power plant in Hong
Kong and an order from China for digital telephone lines.
</TEXT>
