<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Shares in Hogg fall after profit confusion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Hogg Group, the insurance group, dropped sharply yesterday in
response to unexpectedly low profits and confusion over the way in which the
company's year-end figures were reported.
Pre-tax profits fell by one quarter to Pounds 5.03m in the six months to
June 30, compared with Pounds 6.8m in the first half last year. The shares
fell from 211p to a low of 170p, before closing at 172p.
But an extremely brief set of results omitting most of the detailed figures
was released on the Stock Exchange's regulatory news service early yesterday
morning, which inaccurately showed pre-tax profits at Pounds 5.08m.
That soon led to a report on Extel, the financial news wire, that 'a major
part of the company's interim results statement figures had not been
published by the stock exchange' and that the shares dropped 'in the absence
of sufficient background information'.
The stock exchange published a more complete set of results almost two
hours' later.
To add to the confusion, the London Evening Standard newspaper also reported
the decline in Hogg's profits inaccurately in its first edition, and later
blanked out parts of the story at the request of the company.
Hogg said the stock exchange had slipped up. But the exchange insisted that
the company had failed to provide all the information, and the second
statement was issued after a missing page in the press release had been
supplied.
The stock exchange said it had asked Extel to make a correction, arguing
that the wire service report had suggested inaccurately that it was at
fault.
Hogg's results were reduced partly as a result of Pounds 1.2m in costs from
unexpected cancellations of contracts placed last year through Downes &amp;
Burke, its fine arts and jewellery division.
Profits were boosted by Pounds 1.1m in exchange gains from dollar brokerage
and currency translation at higher rates than last year. It said the
underlying growth in worldwide brokerage was 2.3 per cent up on the first
half last year.
Turnover rose to Pounds 62.7m, from Pounds 56.1m, earnings per share were
4.71p, against 6p, and the interim dividend was maintained at 3.15p.
</TEXT>
