<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is always salutary for the English to be reminded of how much the world
owes to the Scottish genius for invention. Small Objects of Desire (BBC 2,
10.10) is an ingenious and worthwhile series. Tonight it examines the
influence on our lives of the hypodermic syringe which was invented in 1853
by a Scottish physician called Alexander Wood.
Critical Eye: The Women at Ten Downing Street (C4, 9.00) follows the
wearisome and depressing course of a strike at a metal furnishing factory in
the West Midlands. Asian women are not a group who have yet made much of a
mark in this country for their militancy. In this case, bad pay, compulsory
overtime and poor working conditions led to the women picketting the factory
for over a year.
American fiction and cinema has gained greatly for putting convicts into
chain-gangs, something which so far as I know the British penal system has
not used this century. 'Cool Hand Luke' with Paul Newman is one of my
favourite films so I will ignore the critical consensus and watch Brubaker
(C4, 10.00) in which another Old Delectable, Robert Redford, swings his
hammer.
</TEXT>
