<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Pools heir hopes to draw 100,000 to gallery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEIR to the Littlewoods pools empire yesterday announced plans to
develop an art gallery to rival the country's leading collections.
The gallery will be part of a new centre for exhibitions and the performing
arts.
Mr Peter Moores aims to open the gallery within five years at Compton
Verney, a mansion near Stratford-upon-Avon in Warwickshire. Mr Moores is a
son of Sir John Moores, the Littlewoods founder who died at the weekend.
The project is being overseen by the Peter Moores Foundation, a charity
which purchased the 18th century mansion last week for an undisclosed sum.
It was bought from Period &amp; Country Houses, the London-based restoration
company.
Foundation officials said that the purchase price, development costs and
budget set aside to expand Mr Moores' private art collection would run into
'several million pounds'.
Separately, another charity aims to build a Pounds 50m opera and ballet
house in the grounds of the estate pending a public inquiry and approval
from the Department of the Environment.
Stratford district council has already approved the scheme, which involves a
1,150-seat auditorium. If planning permission is also granted by the
department, the opera and ballet house would take two years to build and
would open in 1997.
Sir Kenneth Bradshaw, administrator of the Compton Verney Opera Project,
said yesterday the charity would seek backing from private and institutional
investors for the Pounds 40m construction and a Pounds 10m endowment fund to
underwrite running costs.
'This will be the UK's only purpose-built auditorium for both opera and
ballet, and together with the gallery it will be a remarkable arts centre
for the country,' Sir Kenneth said.
The Peter Moores Foundation said the costs of setting up the gallery would
be funded from Mr Moores' own resources.
More than 100,000 visitors a year are expected to visit the gallery when it
opens in the late 1990s.
</TEXT>
