<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Rifkind dismisses rearguard action to save Rosyth yard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A REARGUARD campaign in favour of Scotland's Rosyth naval dockyard foundered
yesterday when the government confirmed that it was to concentrate refitting
of nuclear submarines at the rival Devonport yard in Plymouth.
The announcement by Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, came after three
months of talks with unions, dockyard companies, MPs and private-sector
repairers.
'No new considerations have been put forward which would cause the
government to change its original proposal,' Mr Rifkind said.
The submarine work is worth up to Pounds 5bn over the next 20 years. The
decision to do it in upgraded facilities at Devonport was announced in June
after a two-year battle between the dockyards.
Rosyth can expect one contract to refit a Swiftsure class submarine before
losing this part of its business in 1996. In compensation, it has been
promised a work programme including refits of 18 warships up to 2005.
Babcock Thorn, which runs the government-owned yard, said it was seeking
firm guarantees for these contracts or alternative work. The announcement
came as no surprise as the yard had assumed the decision was unlikely to
change. It was confident the yard was still 'a solid and viable business'.
The decision paves the way for the next stage in dockyard privatisation. The
Ministry of Defence is expected in the next three or four months to issue
invitations to tender for the management and possible ownership of dockyard
facilities.
Management contracts with Babcock Thorn and Devonport Management were due to
expire next year, but have been extended.
