<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Press white paper set for further delays
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has delayed a white paper on privacy and the press amid
disagreements among ministers and a growing realisation of the complexity of
issues involved.
The National Heritage Department first promised a white paper before the
summer recess, then suggested that the document, expected to propose a
'voluntary' ombudsman in addition to the industry's Press Complaints
Commission, would come during the recess.
The most recent hope was that Mr Peter Brooke, national heritage secretary,
would make an announcement at next week's Conservative conference in
Blackpool where a number of motions on the press have been submitted.
The heritage department said Mr Brooke had written to Mr Gerald Kaufman,
chairman of the Commons national heritage committee admitting the government
response to its report on the subject would be delayed. It is likely there
will not be a white paper until next year. Mr Brooke has decided to wait
until responses to the Lord Chancellor's privacy green paper have been
assessed. Responses must be in by October 15.
Ms Patsy Chapman, editor of the News of the World and a former complaints
commission member, said: 'I think the truth is that there are no complaints
about newspapers. The commission is hard-pressed to find complaints from
readers, and really it's politicians who are concerned about privacy and the
press, not the ordinary public.'
The Lord Chancellor's office has proposed a law giving citizens the right to
sue for up to Pounds 10,000 in damages for invasion of privacy.
The delay also means that new criminal offences covering electronic
eavesdropping and the taking of pictures on private property are unlikely to
be included in the Criminal Justice Bill. There have been problems of
definition and arguments over whether there should be a defence of public
interest in the offences.
Lord McGregor, chairman of the complaints commission, and other commission
members have said they will resign if an ombudsman is appointed.
</TEXT>
