<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Warning on photocopier lease 'ruses'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS evidence of 'unacceptable practices' in the photocopier leasing
market, Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of Fair Trading, said
yesterday. He called on the industry to reform itself, warning that he would
take direct action otherwise.
Sir Bryan's remarks follow widespread complaints in the past year about
contracts issued by some photocopier dealers, which are alleged to involve
customers in hidden costs and enormous cancellation fees. An Office of Fair
Trading investigation into the office equipment leasing market was launched
in February.
Sir Bryan said the OFT report, which is expected late next month, 'will
illustrate the seriousness and variety of the malpractices and excesses that
have occurred'.
He said some of the main sufferers had been small businesses, solicitors,
accountants, schools and housing associations. 'Some of these have found
themselves facing five or even six-figure bills to extricate themselves from
contracts.'
Sir Bryan said there were various steps he could take to stop abuses. These
included a reference of the photocopier leasing industry to the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission, and revocation of individual licences.
However, he said, there were signs of change in the industry. 'I hope . . .
that this will be sufficient to make the market work well without regulatory
intervention.'
