<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Portillo stresses need for incentives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL PORTILLO, chief Treasury secretary, last night gave a fresh hint
that the government was disinclined to raise income tax or corporation tax
in the November Budget.
In a speech focusing on declining European competitiveness, Mr Portillo
argued that low rates of both these taxes acted as an important lure for
mobile entrepreneurial talent and investment capital.
The EC was pricing its workers out of jobs by putting too little emphasis on
productivity, profitability and labour market flexibility and too much on
welfare, he warned.
Mr Portillo urged member states to reform their social security systems 'not
only to contain growth in costs to a sustainable level but to give people
greater incentives to work and save'.
His remarks came within 24 hours of Mr Kenneth Clarke's hint that any Budget
tax increases would be on spending rather than incomes.
