<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / VAT on fuel 'will cut energy use'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUTTING value added tax on domestic fuel will reduce household use of energy
by 6 per cent, a report from the Institute for Fiscal Studies says today.
It says the impact will be felt most heavily by low-income households, which
spend a higher-than-average proportion of their income on fuel. The poorest
20 per cent of households will cut energy consumption by 9 per cent but
still face increases in energy costs of 2 per cent of their total spending.
For average households, the extra tax will be about 1.1 per cent of their
total spending.
The government needs to spend an extra Pounds 430m on social security
benefits next year to compensate for the tax increase, the institute says.
The tax, which was announced in the March Budget, has created a political
row that is likely to dominate next week's Conservative conference. VAT will
be charged on domestic fuel at 8 per cent from April next year and at 17.5
per cent a year later.
Increased fuel prices will eventually feed through into higher social
security benefits through the annual indexation process, but the institute
says that indexation - based on average households - is likely to be less
than the poorest families need to cover their increase in fuel bills. It
will also come through a year after the charges are imposed.
The institute recommends bringing forward the indexation of benefits in the
first year, so that benefits rise at the time VAT is imposed - this would
cost Pounds 330m in 1994-95. It also recommends additional help for
pensioners to recognise the importance of heating bills in the budgets of
the elderly. Adjustments to means-tested benefits to double the compensation
paid to the elderly would cost Pounds 100m.
Although the measure has been taken largely to boost tax revenues, the
government has stressed the environmental benefits of the tax in lower
energy consumption.
The institute says VAT 'would be less efficient at restraining carbon
dioxide emissions' from burning fuel than the carbon tax proposed by the
European Commission.
A MORI opinion poll in The Times today says that 92 per cent of all voters
and 83 per cent of Tory voters are against the imposition of VAT on domestic
fuel. A total of 94 per cent of all voters oppose VAT on children's clothes
and 80 per cent VAT on books.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
