<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Printing employers divided on pay change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRINTING employers are divided over whether there should be a return to
national wage bargaining in the industry next year.
After widespread but inconclusive consultation with its 2,600 affiliated
member companies, the British Printing Industries Federation has decided to
hold talks with the GPMU print union over the future of the national
agreement which was suspended this year.
Mr Tony Dubbins, the union's general secretary, welcomed the invitation to
talks yesterday and he stressed this would be without conditions on the
union's side.
The leadership of the employers' federation made clear in recent months that
it wanted to scrap the national agreement for pay while retaining it for
other issues such as training, resolving disputes and health and safety.
Mr Andrew Brown, the federation's employee relations director, said
yesterday that opinions over a return to national bargaining were 'evenly
balanced' among companies. 'There is no definitive position either way - no
clear indication of what to do,' he said.
He added that, if national bargaining returned, the union would have to make
a 'positive response' to the needs of employers who want to introduce
greater flexibility into pay deals and achieve a low-cost agreement.
The union has threatened to withdraw from all its national agreements with
printing employers if industry-wide bargaining is scrapped.
</TEXT>
