<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / BA fuels fight for off-season travellers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AIRWAYS yesterday started an incentive war to attract passengers
during the slack winter season.
The company's Pounds 15m promotion doubles the benefits of its Frequent
Flyer programme for the next six months. Passengers buying full-price
tickets in any class will get double 'air miles' towards free tickets.
Passengers must say by the end of March where they want to fly. The time
limit for taking the flight varies according to the country of residence of
the traveller.
The UK's other scheduled long-haul carrier, Virgin Atlantic Airways, will
soon announce its own incentives. This will include new ways of collecting
Frequent Flyer points. There are links with American Express, Air New
Zealand, British Midland and Scandinavian Airline System.
Virgin and American Express will spend Pounds 3m on a promotional programme
and the airline plans to announce several more partners.
United Airlines, one of the biggest US carriers, is preparing direct
mailshots offering bonus points for trips this winter, while Japan Air Lines
is already four weeks into a double-points promotion.
BA's promotion differs from many others because it forces travellers to
specify their free destination.
</TEXT>
