<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Recession hits tax revenues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION helped push tax revenues down to the lowest levels for five
years in 1992-93, the Inland Revenue said yesterday.
Receipts from compliance and the number of successful prosecutions also
fell, while bad debts, tax written off and costs as a proportion of tax
collected rose.
Net receipts fell to Pounds 76.1bn in the 12 months to March this year
against Pounds 79.7bn last year, the Revenue's annual report showed. That
included net receipts from income tax of Pounds 56.5bn and from corporation
tax of Pounds 16bn.
The Revenue said the decline had been caused by falling income and profits
as a result of the recession and tax changes introduced in the last Budget.
Sir Anthony Battishill, Revenue chairman, said in his foreword to the
report: 'Staff in tax offices achieved the best recorded overall results for
their annual cycle of work and performed extremely well against targets
which measure their service to the tax-paying public.'
Total income from compliance work - including investigations against tax
evasion and avoidance - also fell, to Pounds 4.6bn from Pounds 4.9bn. The
proportion of collectable assessed tax which was collected fell from 87 per
cent to 86.7 per cent as a result of poorer debt collection rates.
The Revenue's expenses fell slightly to Pounds 1.6bn, but the reduction was
not sufficient to offset the decline in tax revenues. As a result, costs as
a proportion of total tax yield rose to the highest level in the past
decade, at 2.09 per cent compared with 2.06 per cent last year.
The amount of tax written off as irrecoverable almost doubled to Pounds
1.7bn last year, from Pounds 884m in 1991. This included Pounds 1.1bn in
unpaid income tax and Pounds 542m in corporation tax.
The number of people convicted in criminal proceedings brought by the
Revenue fell to 217, the lowest level in more than five years, while those
acquitted rose to 14.
Most of the Revenue's offices achieved their performance targets. The
results of an opinion poll in the report show that taxpayers' top priorities
are getting their tax right first time, clear explanations and good general
information. Two thirds said they were satisfied overall with the service
they received.
Seventeen tax inquiry centres experimented with extended opening hours
during the year as part of the Revenue's attempts to restructure.
Nearly 1,500 of the Revenue's tax forms were reviewed during the year
against a target of 1,000 in an attempt to make them clearer.
Report of the Commissioners of the Inland Revenue. Cmnd 2328. HMSO. Pounds
13.90.
</TEXT>
