<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 93 / Smith wins 'democracy' vote: Narrow victory for
one-member-one-vote after unity plea from Prescott
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH stamped his authority on the Labour party last night with a
narrow but critical victory in his battle to inject greater democracy into
links with trade unions.
After a day of drama and intrigue at the party's Brighton conference, the
Labour leader declared that the decision in favour of a one-member-one-vote
(Omov) system to select parliamentary candidates marked 'a great day for the
Labour party'.
Earlier he had gambled his leadership on the outcome, arguing that without a
willingness to inject democracy into its own decision-making, Labour could
not win the trust of the electorate at a general election.
In a nail-biting conclusion, Mr Smith secured the 47.5 per cent to 44.3 per
cent margin for his plan only after a last-minute switch by the MSF
technical union and a powerful plea for unity from Mr John Prescott, the
party's transport spokesman.
But the Labour leader won comfortable majorities for a series of other
constitutional changes that will reduce trade unions' influence at party
conference and in the election of the leader.
The infamous 'block vote' at the annual conference will be replaced by a
system of individual voting by unions, although they will still wield 70 per
cent of the total votes.
Mr Smith said that by drawing a line under the year-long dispute over
internal democracy, the party could move forward 'to advance our agenda for
full employment and social justice'. He added: 'This is an important step
towards victory at the next general election.'
The victory over opposition led by the party's biggest paymasters - the TGWU
and GMB general unions - was not without confusion. Although the delegates
passed the vital change in party rules sought by Mr Smith, it also supported
a conflicting motion proposed by the TGWU. Mr Bill Morris, the TGWU general
secretary, indicated that his union would continue its battle against Omov.
That stance, however, was brushed aside by Mr Smith, who insisted that the
change was irreversible.
Mr John Edmonds of the GMB indicated that he would accept the outcome,
saying the party leadership and the unions could unite behind Mr Smith's
policies for the economy and welfare state. Mr Edmonds added, however, a
warning that any further attempts to diminish the role of the unions would
provoke another damaging battle.
The excruciatingly narrow victory followed a day of arm-twisting, pleading
and cajoling to secure enough votes for Mr Smith. Mr Neil Kinnock, the
former party leader who began the process of reform, emerged as a pivotal
figure in winning over waverers to his successor.
Among the extraordinary tactics employed to persuade smaller trade unions -
and crucially to assure the neutrality of the MSF - was a warning from Mr
Smith that a defeat would wreck separate plans to promote the role of women
in the party.
The other critical point was a passionate address to the conference by Mr
Prescott, a leading figure on the left and a much-trusted figure among
unions. Mr Prescott's unequivocal backing for the proposals contrasted
sharply with attempts by Mrs Margaret Beckett, Mr Smith's deputy, to
distance herself from the plans.
That in turn raised strong speculation - openly encouraged by some members
of the shadow cabinet - that Mr Prescott will face pressure to challenge Mrs
Beckett for the deputy leadership next year.
Leading 'modernisers' in the senior ranks of the party said Labour could
resume the process of dumping the 'ideological baggage' that had cost it
four election defeats. But Mr Smith's declared aim of strengthening rather
than weakening the party's links with the unions were taken as evidence by
many on the left - including Mr Prescott - that he would not risk another
confrontation.
Mr John Major last night accused Mr Smith of surrendering to the unions over
his party's reforms. 'It's policy that people care about and as far as
policy is concerned the unions are still calling the tune and John Smith is
receiving the message on his knees,' he said.
