<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / International Company News: Vontobel link to Swiss bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VONTOBEL Holding, the Zurich-based private banking group, has taken an
agreed one-third stake in Tardy, de Watteville &amp; Cie, a small Geneva private
bank. It plans to raise its share to two-thirds within two years. The price
paid - in cash and shares - was not disclosed.
The move represents a first step along the path mapped out last May by Mr
Hans-Dieter Vontobel, chairman of Vontobel Holding, to ensure an independent
future for the family-controlled group.
The three existing partners of Tardy, de Watteville will continue to run the
Geneva bank, which employs 55 people and had a balance sheet of SFr94m
(Dollars 64.9m) at the end of July. One partner, Mr Bernard de Watteville,
is to be proposed to the Vontobel board.
Mr Vontobel said the transaction fitted in with plans to reduce the family
shareholding, while ensuring the group remained independent. He hopes to do
this by enlarging the group of shareholders actively involved in management,
as well as by increasing the proportion of shares held by the public from
the present one-third to over a half.
The partnership with Tardy, de Watteville gives Vontobel a presence in
Geneva, a leading private banking centre, and access to new francophone
markets. Vontobel, a quoted company with 540 employees, had an end-1992
balance sheet of SFr1.49bn, and posted group net profits of SFr24.5m last
year.
</TEXT>
