<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (29): A pleasant place to do business - Best
cuisine in Latin America
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID PILLING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIMA does not have a pretty reputation. A bloated population, mushrooming
slums, terrorism and economic chaos have seen to that. One Peruvian
commentator, writing in the mid-1980s, complained bitterly of attacks,
kidnappings, rapes and murders, characteristics which, he said, had
'coincided with increasingly aggressive driving habits.'
Wayward driving is still all-too obvious, but Lima itself is in many ways
one of Latin America's more pleasant capitals. The phone system works,
violence has abated, bureaucracy is minimal and Peruvian cuisine is often
excellent.
A 1960s description of Lima as an open, airy place may strike some as a
little ironic of a city often enveloped in mist and pollution. Nonetheless,
Lima can be an enjoyable place in which to do business.
Airport: Customs formalities are fairly straightforward. No visas are
required for citizens of western Europe, the US, Canada, Japan or most Latin
American countries. There are no restrictions on bringing in or taking out
currency. If you are staying for more than two weeks, you may be required to
pay a tax (refundable on leaving the country) on electronic items. There is
a Dollars 17.50 airport tax payable on international flights. A taxi from
the airport can cost anything from Dollars 10-Dollars 30. Haggle.
Hotels: Most business people stay in Miraflores, a coastal suburb about a
20-minute drive from downtown Lima. Now the capital's main social centre,
Miraflores is spilling over with restaurants, shops and hotels. Hotels
include El Condado (Alcanfores 465, tel: 443 614); Miraflores Cesar (La Paz
y Diez Canseco, tel: 441 212) and Las Americas (Av. Benavides 415, tel: 459
494). All three have air conditioning, satellite TV, fax service, bars and
restaurants. For longer visits you might consider one of Miraflores' many
short-stay apartment blocks.
The downtown Lima area has many beautiful old hotels, among them the Grand
Bolivar (Union 958, tel: 276 400). Even if you do not stay here, it can be a
wonderful place to have a pisco sour (Peru's national drink) on the terrace.
There is also the Sheraton (Paseo de la Republica, tel: 333 320). In the
off-season it is usually possible to negotiate substantial discounts. All
hotels add on taxes of up to 30 per cent.
Personal security: Sendero bombings are much less frequent since the capture
of Abimael Guzman, although an attack on the US embassy in July demonstrates
that the terrorist threat is not yet a thing of the past. President Fujimori
is fond of saying that Lima is no more dangerous than Florence, London or
New York - a claim somewhat negated by the number of heavily armed guards
stationed outside most office buildings.
Many offices require you to leave some form of picture identification at
reception before entering. It is probably best to carry a driving licence or
a photocopy of your passport. (One FT employee found his London Underground
travel pass perfectly adequate.)
As in any big city, walking around aimlessly at night is probably not a good
idea. Robbery is not uncommon (robbery with violence is). But there is no
need for the paranoia exhibited by some visitors. Miraflores and San Isidro
are generally safe.
Transport: Most large hotels have official cabs stationed outside which can
be hired per trip or for the day. Hotel cars have the advantage of being a
little more comfortable, safer (most have seat belts) and the driver is
likely to know where he is going.
But do not rule out flagging down some of the dilapidated Volkswagens which
ply Lima's streets. It is useful to know the name of a landmark near to your
final destination, as taxi drivers (often off-duty military or out-of-work
salesmen) sometimes do not know their way around too well. Fix a price
before you get in.
Internal flights to the main cities are frequent, if not regular. Early
morning flights tend to leave on time, but as the day wears on the timetable
can slip.
Leave plenty of time for connecting flights. Faucett (336 364), AeroPeru
(478 333), Americana (478 662), Expresso Aereo (452 545) and AeroCondor (425
663) all run services to main provincial towns.
Telephones: Peru's telephone service is probably pitched somewhere between
that of Mexico and Chile. It is usually fairly easy to dial direct but line
quality is sometimes poor, especially for sending data. International calls
can also be made through the operator on 108.
Restaurants: Peruvians boast that their cuisine is the best in Latin
America, a sentiment echoed by many visitors. Hotel food is often expensive
and internationalised and it is usually better to eat out. Seafood is often
excellent and highly spiced.
Ceviche is a cold dish of seafood, onion and hot green pepper. There is also
chupe de camorones, a shrimp stew, as well as potato dishes such as causa
and carapulcra. Olives are big and succulent. Coffee can also be very good -
for a strong espresso coffee with milk as drunk in Europe or the US, ask for
a cortado. You should also try Inca Kola at least once: a bubble-gum
flavoured soft drink which is Peru's answer to its more famous international
counterparts.
Recommended restaurants in Miraflores include: La Trattoria for home-made
pasta and imaginative salads (Manuel Bonilla 106, tel: 467 002); Rosa
Nautica, built on a pier, opulent (Espigon no 4, Lima bay, tel: 470 057);
Costa Verde, also with wonderful views of Pacific and good seafood (tel: 772
424); Las Tejas, a moderately priced Peruvian restaurant with good fish and
chicken dishes (Diez Canseco 340, tel: 444 360). Luigi's (Benavides) is
excellent for breakfast while Haiti (Diagonal) is a good place for coffee
and a snack.
Health: It is probably advisable to drink bottled water, although it is
perfectly safe to brush your teeth with tap water. As in most developing
countries, be wary of eating salads. Drinks are probably better sin hielo
(without ice). Ask instead for your drink bien helada (refrigerated).
Some Peruvian food is highly spiced. While most of it is perfectly safe to
eat you may find your stomach reacting a little to the change of cuisine.
The cholera epidemic, prevalent in 1991, has largely passed and is not
likely to affect you.
Weekend trips: Paracas is a coastal resort about two hours' drive from Lima.
Not only does it often have sun in winter, when Lima is soaking in damp
mist, but also it has a seal colony and a marine reserve. The Hotel Paracas
is comfortable and has excellent food (reservations in Lima, 465 079).
An hour or so beyond Paracas is the superb hotel Las Dunas, at Ica, another
favourite weekend retreat for capital-dwellers, especially in winter. Enjoy
sun or sand-surfing, or visit some of the local vineyards. Pisco, Peru's
famous grape brandy, is made near here. You can also take a small aircraft
and overfly the amazing Nazca lines. (Las Dunas - reservations in Lima, 424
180).
Also available for the sports-minded is white-water rafting. Closest to Lima
is in the pretty Canete valley, about two hours away. Ask a tour agency
(like Lima Tours, tel: 276 624) to make reservations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>PEZ  Peru, South America.
</CN>
<XX>
