<DATE>930929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (23): High export potential - There is almost
no known crop which cannot be grown in Peru
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOTHING could look less like prime agricultural land than Peru's coastal
strip, a 2,800km ribbon of greyish moonscape desert where rain never falls.
Yet there are 760,000 hectares of irrigated land already available, ideal
for a wide variety of export fruit and vegetable crops - about five times
the area on which Chile's agro-industrial boom is based.
There is almost no known crop which cannot be grown somewhere in Peru. The
coast is particularly well suited to high-price export crops such as
asparagus, melon, tomatoes, grapes, broccoli and snow peas. The temperate
climate and absence of rain means that there are effectively no seasons, so
produce can be harvested year round and 'windows' in international markets
exploited.
For years, Peruvian and foreign agriculturalists have been aware of this
potential. Until recently, however, legislation on land tenure has prevented
development.
Under the land reform enacted by General Velasco's military government 25
years ago, huge, privately-owned coastal haciendas were turned into
co-operatives. Elsewhere, minifundios - tiny plots worked by a single family
 -proliferated. A downward spiral of inefficiency and decapitalisation
converted Peru from a once flourishing exporter of sugar, rice and cotton to
a net importer of all those products.
Peruvian agriculture has now been on the decline for 40 years. In the decade
1950-1960, the sector accounted for more than 20 per cent of gdp. By 1970 it
had fallen below 15 per cent and, for the past 13 years it has hovered at
between 11 and 13 per cent.
'Traditional' exports from the former haciendas - primarily rice, sugar and
cotton - have slumped. Last year, for the first time, 'non-traditional'
produce (asparagus, cocoa, exotic fruits, colourants and so on) overtook the
historically more important crops, earning Dollars 151m in foreign exchange,
Dollars 36m more than their 'traditional' rivals.
'But Peru's potential is only relative unless there are adequate
conditions,' says Mr Salomon Diaz, a cochineal exporter and president of
Adex, the agro-industrial committee of the exporters' association. 'The
state still needs to devise positive export-oriented strategies to convert
Peru into an important agro-industrial exporter.'
Agricultural policy has always focused on big spending projects - irrigation
works more often than not. Research has been starved of funds. It has never
been directed towards identifying opportunities in national and
international markets.
The Fujimori government has laid down some essential foundations for the
modernisation of agriculture. Land has been declared a freely tradeable
commodity, strict land-holding limits have been relaxed and foreigners put
on an equal footing with Peruvian nationals for investment purposes.
Advances against terrorism have brought relative tranquillity back to the
countryside. Taming inflation has been especially important for medium to
long term activities such as farming.
But serious problems remain. 'Less than ten per cent of Peruvian farmers
hold legal title to their land, which prevents them using it as collateral
for credit,' says Mr Diaz. 'Then, financing costs - at about 18 per cent a
year - are absurdly high. So are costs of energy and transport.'
In the Andean highlands there is no agricultural land left. The jungle has
some 4,000 hectares suitable for cultivation, but lack of roads and
transport infrastructure renders this land almost useless. At least in the
short term, development must therefore centre on the coastal strip.
Here the old haciendas, now co-operatives, remain in possession of some of
the best irrigated coastal land. But according to Mr Diaz, they are wasting
the scarce resource of water by growing thirsty crops like rice and
sugar-cane.
'Peru's coast has the great advantage that, because there's no rain,
irrigation is man-managed. With high technology methods - drip or sprinkler
systems - we could irrigate four times the area with the same amount of
water we're now expending on crops we'd do better to import.'
Modern irrigation methods mean that even a five-hectare plot (and two-thirds
of all Peruvian farmers have less than that) becomes economically viable if
intensively cultivated with high-value export products. 'But the farmer
needs support from the state to switch. A Chilean farmer can bring in
irrigation equipment and claw back the import tariffs once he starts
exporting. We can't,' says Mr Diaz.
Mr Carlos Bolona, a former economy minister, would promote change and
efficiency in the sector by different means. 'Until the state charges
farmers a realistic price for the water they consume,' he says, 'they'll
never switch from the 'easy' crops to valuable export products.'
So far, the star of those crops is asparagus; exports last year topped
Dollars 26m. Export values of mangoes, mandarine oranges, grapes, apples and
bananas all stand at about Dollars 5m a year, the point at which, according
to Mr Diaz, they create their own export momentum and you can 'stop worrying
about them'. 1992 export earnings from cocoa products totalled over Dollars
13m. Colourants (marigold, annatto, cochineal and carmine) brought in
Dollars 24m. Principal buyers were the US and, in Europe, the Low Countries,
followed by Germany and Spain.
Agro-industry, in a small way, already exists in each of Peru's widely
distinct geographical zones and each specialises in a different range of
crops. The northern coast produces high-quality mangoes, bananas, passion
fruit and lemon-limes; the centre: asparagus, broccoli, green beans,
snow-peas and grapes; the south: beans (which have considerable export
potential), garlic, onions and oregano.
'All these are products in international demand, which Peruvian farmers have
long experience in growing,' says Mr Diaz. 'It wouldn't be difficult to
double or triple export quality output in the short term.'
The Andes and the jungle, too, have their own specialities. Peru's high
mountains (home of the potato) produce high-protein grains such as quinua
and kiwicha, which are starting to acquire an international reputation.
Other products include tarwi, a host of medicinal plants and herbs and the
colourant cochineal, of which Peru is the world's leading producer.
Descending the eastern slopes of the Andes towards the Amazon basin, crops
give way to world-class coffee and cocoa, annatto and every conceivable
tropical fruit.
'We're sleeping on our comparative advantages,' warns Mr Diaz. 'One of
Peru's best fruits, which we hardly export, is the chirimoya (custard
apple). But Chile has planted perhaps 400 hectares and is already strongly
entering the international market.'
Paradoxically, it may finally be the Chileans who get things moving in Peru.
Chilean entrepreneurs are in Peru now, sizing up opportunities for land
purchase.
'They've been through this themselves. They're aware that Peru's climatic
conditions are even better than their own - they know it's going to be
excellent business,' says Mr Bolona.
